Importing the libraries¶

All the necessary libraries are imported, each library has a following commented line stating the using of the library in this assignment

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
# Pandas library helps in extracting the data from csv or excel files 
# into the dataframe and then further manipulating the data according to the necessary format

import numpy as np
# Numpy library helps in statistical calculation and also ploting the best fit line for each state in the assignment

import seaborn as sns
# Seaborn is another visualization library which can be used to plot various charts like, Bar Chart, Pie Chart etc.

import math
# Math library is used to do some basic mathematical operations like square roots etc.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Matplotlib is a visualization library which can be used to plot various charts like, Bar Chart, Pie Chart etc.

pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('display.max_rows', None)

%matplotlib inline
# The above command is a magical command for ploting graphs in jupyter notebook

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

Data Preperation¶

Converting all the binary categories to 0/1 (Label Encodig)¶

In [4]:
# Converting Yes to 1 and No to 0
leadscr_data['Do Not Email'] = leadscr_data['Do Not Email'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Do Not Call'] = leadscr_data['Do Not Call'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Search'] = leadscr_data['Search'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Magazine'] = leadscr_data['Magazine'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Newspaper Article'] = leadscr_data['Newspaper Article'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['X Education Forums'] = leadscr_data['X Education Forums'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Newspaper'] = leadscr_data['Newspaper'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Digital Advertisement'] = leadscr_data['Digital Advertisement'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Through Recommendations'] = leadscr_data['Through Recommendations'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Receive More Updates About Our Courses'] = leadscr_data['Receive More Updates About Our Courses'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Update me on Supply Chain Content'] = leadscr_data['Update me on Supply Chain Content'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['Get updates on DM Content'] = leadscr_data['Get updates on DM Content'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['I agree to pay the amount through cheque'] = leadscr_data['I agree to pay the amount through cheque'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
leadscr_data['A free copy of Mastering The Interview'] = leadscr_data['A free copy of Mastering The Interview'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})

In [6]:
# Removing ID columns
leadscr_data = leadscr_data.drop(['Prospect ID','Lead Number'], axis=1) 

# Dropping columns with values same in all rows - useless feature for prediction ; 0 variance
leadscr_data= leadscr_data.loc[:,leadscr_data.nunique()!=1]

# Removing columns with high biased values
leadscr_data = leadscr_data.drop(['Do Not Call','Search','Newspaper Article','Newspaper','Through Recommendations','What matters most to you in choosing a course','How did you hear about X Education'], axis=1)

# Dropping the columns 'Asymmetrique Activity Score' & 'Asymmetrique Profile Score' as they are same as their index columns
leadscr_data = leadscr_data.drop(['Asymmetrique Activity Score','Asymmetrique Profile Score'], axis=1)
In [7]:
## Nul Value Imputation
# Continuous with median
leadscr_data['TotalVisits'].replace(np.NaN, leadscr_data['TotalVisits'].median(), inplace =True)
leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'].replace(np.NaN, leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'].median(), inplace =True)

# Categorical with mode
leadscr_data.loc[pd.isnull(leadscr_data['Country']), ['Country']] = leadscr_data['Country'].mode()[0]

# Treating highly biased column country
leadscr_data['Country'] = leadscr_data['Country'].apply(lambda x: 'India' if x=='India' else 'Abroad')
print(leadscr_data['Country'].value_counts())
print()
# Lead quality column has more null values and cannot be dropped for its importance
print(leadscr_data['Lead Quality'].value_counts())
print()
print(leadscr_data['Lead Quality'].isnull().sum())

# Instead of removong data we can fill it with Unknown response as the selection was not mandatory from the website the data was scraped from
leadscr_data['Lead Quality'].fillna("Unknown", inplace = True)
print(leadscr_data['Lead Quality'].value_counts())

In [22]:
# Outlier analysis

Q1 = leadscr_data['TotalVisits'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = leadscr_data['TotalVisits'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
leadscr_data=leadscr_data.loc[(leadscr_data['TotalVisits'] >= Q1 - 1.5*IQR) & (leadscr_data['TotalVisits'] <= Q3 + 1.4*IQR)]

Q1 = leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
leadscr_data=leadscr_data.loc[(leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'] >= Q1 - 1.5*IQR) & (leadscr_data['Page Views Per Visit'] <= Q3 + 1.5*IQR)]

leadscr_data.shape

Normalization¶

3 columns are normalized they are: TotalVisits Total Time Spent on Website Page Views Per Visit

In [24]:
# Normalising continuous features
df = leadscr_data[["TotalVisits", "Total Time Spent on Website", "Page Views Per Visit"]]
### Columns that are required to be normalized

normalized_df=(df-df.mean())/df.std()
leadscr_data = leadscr_data.drop(["TotalVisits", "Total Time Spent on Website", "Page Views Per Visit"], 1)
# dropping the columns normalized
    
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data,normalized_df],axis=1)

Data Encoding¶

Encoding variables having more than 2 categories

In [25]:
# Encoding the categorical variables
dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Lead Origin"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Lead Origin'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)



dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Lead Source"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Lead Source'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)


dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Last Activity"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Last Activity'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)



dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Country"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Country'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)



dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Specialization"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Specialization'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)




dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["What is your current occupation"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['What is your current occupation'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)



dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Tags"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Tags'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)


dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Lead Quality"]
dataset_LS = pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Lead Quality'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)


dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["Lead Profile"]
pd.get_dummies(dataset_LS,prefix=['Lead Profile'], drop_first=True)
leadscr_data = pd.concat([leadscr_data, dataset_LS], axis=1)


dataset_LS = pd.DataFrame()
dataset_LS = leadscr_data["City"]

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE

print(rfe.ranking_)           # Printing the ranking

VIF's¶

# Check for the VIF values of the feature variables. 
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

X_train = sm.add_constant(X_train)

lr_2 = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train).fit()

# Print the summary of the model
print(lr_2.summary())

# Create a dataframe that will contain the names of all the feature variables and their respective VIFs
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif['Features'] = X_train.columns
vif['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_train.values, i) for i in range(X_train.shape[1])]
vif['VIF'] = round(vif['VIF'], 2)
vif = vif.sort_values(by = "VIF", ascending = False)
vif

In [73]:
def draw_roc( actual, probs ):
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve( actual, probs,
                                              drop_intermediate = False )
    auc_score = metrics.roc_auc_score( actual, probs )
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.plot( fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % auc_score )
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate or [1 - True Negative Rate]')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic example')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.savefig("ROC.png")
    plt.show()

    return fpr, tpr, thresholds
